<DOC><DOCNO> AP890124-0248 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1131EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-Chrysler-NAACP     01-24 0157</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Chrysler-NAACP,0165</SECOND><HEAD>Chrysler Joins NAACP in Minority Program</HEAD><DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Chrysler Corp. said it has beguntalks with the NAACP to advance job opportunities for minorities.   In a joint announcement with the civil rights group releasedMonday, Chrysler said it would work toward a ``fair share''agreement.   ``We believe we have a good record with our minority programs,''Chairman Lee Iacocca said in a written statement. ``But as thesaying goes, almost everything can stand improvement.''   Benjamin Hooks, executive director of the National Associationfor the Advancement of Colored People, said, ``We are pleased thatthe Chrysler Corporation, as a good corporate citizen, has respondedpositively to our request for discussion of a fair share agreement.''   The Fair Share Program, in effect since 1982, is aimed atexpanding opportunities for minorities.   General Motors Corp. earlier signed a fair share agreement withthe NAACP, and Ford Motor Co. signed a similar agreement in Chicago.</TEXT></DOC>